import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib import rc
import seaborn as sns

Base figure code

f, ax = plt.subplots()
x = [i for i in range(10)]
y = [i**2 for i in x]
ax.plot(x, y)
ax.set_xlabel('x')
ax.set_ylabel('y');

Plot 1

Change it so that the x axis label is and the y axis label is . Those are the Greek letters sigma and tau, respectively.

Take the same plot, and change the x axis label to 2s.

For the same plot as above, change the plot so that the line is red, dot-dash, and 3 times the default line thickness.

f, ax = plt.subplots()
x = [i for i in range(10)]
y = [i**2 for i in x]
# The default linewidth is 1.5, so multiply that by 3
ax.plot(x, y, color='red', linewidth=3*1.5, linestyle='dashdot')
ax.set_xlabel('$\sigma2s$')
ax.set_ylabel('$\\tau$')
plt.show()

Plot 2

Take the graph we started with, and assume theres a variable y = 7. Add a title to the graph that says =7. (Thats the Greek letter gamma.) Do it using the variable! Dont hard-code in the value!

y = 7
title = '$\Gamma$' + '=' + str(y)
f, ax = plt.subplots()
x = [i for i in range(10)]
y = [i**2 for i in x]
ax.plot(x, y)
ax.set_xlabel('x')
ax.set_ylabel('y')
plt.title(title)
plt.show()

Plot 3

Take the graph we started with, and assume theres a variable y = 7. Add a text element at coordinates x=0.1, y=0.4 to the graph that says =7.

y = 7
textstr = '$\Gamma$' + '=' + str(y)
f, ax = plt.subplots()
x = [i for i in range(10)]
y = [i**2 for i in x]
ax.plot(x, y)
ax.set_xlabel('x')
ax.set_ylabel('y')
ax.text(0.1, 0.4, textstr)
plt.show()

Saving files

Save one of your graphics in the following formats:

  • pdf with 18 point font, 10" by 10" square
  • tiff with 18 point font, 10" by 10" square and the x axis font is 1/2 the global font size.
  • 72 dpi png with 18 point font, 10" by 10" square
  • 300 dpi png with 18 point font, 10" by 10" square
rc('font', size=18)
f, ax = plt.subplots()
x = [i for i in range(10)]
y = [i**2 for i in x]
ax.plot(x, y)
ax.set_xlabel('x')
ax.set_ylabel('y')
ax.text(0.1, 0.4, textstr)
f.set_size_inches(10, 10)
plt.savefig('save1.pdf')
rc('font', size=18)
f, ax = plt.subplots()
x = [i for i in range(10)]
y = [i**2 for i in x]
ax.plot(x, y)
ax.set_xlabel('x', fontsize=plt.rcParams['font.size']/2)
ax.set_ylabel('y')
ax.text(0.1, 0.4, textstr)
f.set_size_inches(10, 10)
plt.savefig('save2.tiff')
rc('font', size=18)
f, ax = plt.subplots()
x = [i for i in range(10)]
y = [i**2 for i in x]
ax.plot(x, y)
ax.set_xlabel('x')
ax.set_ylabel('y')
ax.text(0.1, 0.4, textstr)
f.set_size_inches(10, 10)
plt.savefig('save3.png', dpi=72)

Base figure

plt.clf()
mtcars = r.mtcars
f = sns.scatterplot(
    data=mtcars, 
    x = 'cyl', 
    y = 'mpg'
)
plt.show()

Plot 1

f = sns.scatterplot(
    data=mtcars, 
    x = 'cyl', 
    y = 'mpg',
    color = 'red',
    s = 450,
    marker = 'x'
)
f.set(xlabel='$\sigma2s$', ylabel='$\\tau$');
plt.show()

Plot 2

y = 7
title = '$\Gamma$' + '=' + str(y)
f = sns.scatterplot(
    data=mtcars, 
    x = 'cyl', 
    y = 'mpg'
)
f.set(title = title)
plt.show()

Plot 3

Note that I moved the coords of the text box so that it would show up.

y = 7
textstr = '$\Gamma$' + '=' + str(y)
f = sns.scatterplot(
    data=mtcars, 
    x = 'cyl', 
    y = 'mpg'
)
f.text(5, 15,textstr)
plt.show()

Multi-panel figures

Plot two plots side by side. (It is fine to plot the same plot next to itself.)

Do it again, but as a 2x2 matrix of 4 plots.

fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=2)
sns.scatterplot(data=mtcars, x = 'cyl', y = 'mpg', ax=axs[0])
sns.scatterplot(data=mtcars, x = 'cyl', y = 'mpg', ax=axs[1])
plt.show()

fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=2, nrows=2)
sns.scatterplot(data=mtcars, x = 'cyl', y = 'mpg', ax=axs[0][0])
sns.scatterplot(data=mtcars, x = 'cyl', y = 'mpg', ax=axs[1][0])
sns.scatterplot(data=mtcars, x = 'cyl', y = 'mpg', ax=axs[0][1])
sns.scatterplot(data=mtcars, x = 'cyl', y = 'mpg', ax=axs[1][1])
plt.show()
